Thulani Gqirana, News24 Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town &ndash; An ANC MP put aside the rule book, ignored the chirps and insults, and opened up his Bible in the National Assembly on Wednesday.MPs were debating President Jacob Zuma&rsquo;s State of the Nation Address. Opposition parties continued poking holes in his speech, while ANC MPs reiterated their support for calls for &ldquo;radical economic transformation&rdquo;.ANC MP Zet Luzipo was however not in the mood to debate, and instead expressed his concern at DA leader Mmusi Maimane&rsquo;s &ldquo;faith&rdquo;.The MP shared four Bible verses with MPs. They were about how those who live by the word of God should live it daily.He said the level of anger Maimane had displayed during the SONA debate was worrying for a preacher.Maimane is a preacher at the Discovery Church in Randburg, Johannesburg.&ldquo;You can&rsquo;t choose when and where to preach. You don&rsquo;t part-time preach the word of God,&rdquo; Luzipo said. &nbsp;Using the podium as a pulpit, he called on Maimane to always preach peace.When MPs questioned the relevance of his sermon, he shot them down.&ldquo;I have never heard of a point of order on a sermon, a word of God,&rdquo; he said.If he was being compelled to return the lost flock to God, he would do so, he said, before closing off with blessing the Bible.&lsquo;Killer of hopes and dreams&rsquo;The second day of the debate was filled with insults, multiple points of order, and the ANC MPs rallying behind Zuma.ANC chief whip Jackson Mthembu hit hard at the Democratic Alliance, accusing the DA of grandstanding for their calls for a moment of silence for the Esidimeni tragedy.He said the DA had ample time to raise the issue through the right channels in Parliament and had instead chosen to &ldquo;use the tragedy as a political football&rdquo;.The EFF were also not spared from Mthembu&rsquo;s wrath.&ldquo;How long are we going to allow the EFF to assault workers of Parliament with hard hats?&rdquo;He said it was time to make a decision on the matter, and said hard hats should be banned from Parliament.Agang MP Andries Tlouamma was in top form as he called Zuma a killer of hopes and dreams.&ldquo;Under his leadership we are being governed by vultures and parasites.&rdquo;He said Zuma, who sat smiling through the insults, personified moral degeneration.He was a disciple of greed and patronage, and he could not be cleansed by a bucketful of perfume, the Agang MP said.African Independent Party leader Mandlenkosi Galo said radical economic transformation was a pie in the sky and &ldquo;code for radical corruption&rdquo;.ANC MPs outlined the importance of the agricultural sector in dealing with poverty and the continued fight for equality in the country.Small Business Development Minister Lindiwe Zulu told MPs that ownership of the means of production must change, the patterns of ownership must change, and that land had to be returned to the people for production and housing.&ldquo;All institutions supporting radical socio-economic transformation must step up.&rdquo;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.